summary.seg: This manuscript is a composite volume and comprises a complete copy of the Bible in Latin made in England in the first half of the 13th century accompanied by four later quires of exegetical material that helped readers to understand the text of the Bible. These quires include Stephen Langton's Interpretationes nominum hebraicorum ('Interpretations of Hebrew names') and Peter of Poitiers' Compendium historiae in genealogia Christi ('Compilation of history in the genealogy of Christ'). They were probably copied in the late 14th or early 15th centuries in England and were presumably incorporated into the volume soon after their creation.

MS Dd.8.12 is one of the last examples of the 'Giant Bibles' produced in the Romanesque decorative style in England in the Middle Ages. The latter half of the 12th century was the high-point of Giant Bible production in England, and the surviving volumes are characterised by their generous dimensions, their preference for the pandect format (i.e., the whole text of the Bible in a single volume), and their exquisite decorative schemes, which made extensive use of opaque polychrome illustration, historiated initials with the figures and scenes typically enclosed in rounded frames, and frequent use of gold as a ground and as a decorative embellishment. Famous giant bibles include:
The 'Bury Bible' ( Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 2 (now bound in 3 parts))
The 'Dover Bible' ( Cambridge, Corpus Christi College, MS 3)
The 'Lambeth Bible' (London, Lambeth Palace Library, MS 3)
The 'Winchester Bible' (Winchester, Cathedral Library, MS 17 and
New York, Morgan Library, MS M.619) By the early 13th century, the highest grade of bible was still exquisitely decorated, but the fashionable format for bibles increasingly tended towards more compact volumes that prioritised comfortable consultation and transport over monumental effect.

This volume has one significant illuminated initial on f. 12r, a historiated 'I' at the start of the Old Testament, the body of the letter filled with scenes illustrating the stages of the creation of the world as described in Genesis. Nigel Morgan noticed similiarities between the initial in MS Dd.8.12 and the programme of decoration in the Ashmole Bestiary ( Oxford, Bodleain Library, MS Ashmole 1511), and placed the production of MS Dd.8.12 among a group of scribes and artists active in either the north Midlands or the north of England in the first third of the 13th century (see N. Morgan, Early Gothic Manuscripts (1) 1190-1250).

Before becoming part of the UL collection in 1664, the manuscript belonged to Richard Holdsworth, who was the Dean of Worcester Cathedral at the time of his death in 1649. Holdsworth was a bibliophile, and by 1649 he had a personal collection of c. 10,000 manuscripts and printed books. After Holdsworth's death there was a great deal of legal disagreement as to the intended beneficiaries of the collection, but eventually, in 1664, probate was settled so that the majority of the collection passed to Cambridge University Library.

Dr Sarah Gilbert
Project Cataloguer, Curious Cures in Cambridge Libraries
Cambridge University Library

collation.p:
The manuscript comprises a 13th-century core of 43 quires that contain the general prefaces to the Bible, and the Old and New Testaments, surrounded by exegetical material in additional quires of the 14th and 15th centuries (Quires a, and 44-46). The manuscript has been rebound at least once and some leaves have been displaced, removed, or altered as part of these rebindings. The quires are arranged as follows:
Quire a8-1 (+2) (ff. i, 1-2, 3-8; 1st missing, 2nd is now the left pastedown, 3rd and 4th are an inserted bifolium) |
Quires 1-2410 (ff. 9-248)
Quire 2512-1 (ff. 249-259; 12th cancelled)
Quires 26-4210 (ff. 260-429)
Quire 4312-1 (ff. 430-440; 1st cancelled) |
Quires 44-4510 (ff. 441-460) |
Quire 468-1 (+2) (ff. 461-467, 469 + 470; 8th missing, ff. 469-470 are an inserted bifolium, f. 469 is affixed to f. 467 with an adhesive, and f. 470 is now the right pastedown)
collation.formula: a8-1 (+2) (1st missing, 2nd is now the left pastedown, 3rd and 4th are an inserted bifolium) | 1-2410 2512-1 (12th cancelled) 26-4210 4312-1 (1st cancelled) | 44-4510 | 468-1 (+2) (8th missing, 7th leaf fixed to 1st leaf of an inserted bifolium with an adhesive, final leaf of bifolium is now the right pastedown)

signatures.p: Quires numbered 'a, 1-46' in the lower outer corner of the first recto of each quire in pencil in Hindu-Arabic numerals. Lower outer corner of the first recto in the second half of each quire marked in pencil with a small '+' symbol. This quire designation schema added in the 20th century.

binding.p: 17th century binding. Rebacked. Fully bound in calf leather over pasteboards with matching decoration to the left and right covers. Covers are each decorated with a blind double-fillet frame inset from the perimeter of the boards by c. 5mm. Head, fore, and tail edges of the boards decorated with a gilt single fillet.

The volume has been rebacked, probably in the 19th century. The replacement back has 7 raised bands, each with a gilt dotted single-fillet across the centre of the band (i.e., across the width of the spine). Spine compartments are decorated along their upper and lower perimeters with a gilt single-fillet. Upper and lower openings of the spine are each decorated with a gilt double-fillet.
Head and tail bands sewn in alternating segments of blue and cream yarn around a core of ?animal-derived cord.
Title label BIBLIA HIERONYMI of Russia leather; the perimeter of the label decorated with two concentric frames: the outer frame a triple-fillet tooled in gold, the inner frame a simple foliate roll.

provenance.p: One of the manuscripts of Richard Holdsworth (1590-1649), Master of Emmanuel College Holdsworth, Richard, 1590-1649 .

history.acquisition: Acquired by the University Library in July 1664: no. 33 in the inventory of Holdsworth's manuscripts compiled chiefly by William Crowe and recorded in MS Ff.4.27 and MS Dd.8.45. The Holdsworth number is recorded as 'vol. 34' on f. 1r.

collation.p: The extant Quire 'a' is incomplete; the original 1st leaf is lost, 7 original leaves remain, and a parchment bifolium has been added. The first extant leaf of Quire 'a' (the second leaf of the original quire) has been used as the left pastedown by a binder, and has the designation f. i. A parchment bifolium has been inserted into the gathering between the first and second extant leaves (now ff. i and 3 respectively), perhaps by the binder who used the first extant leaf as the left pastedown. The two leaves of the added bifolium have the designations ff. 1-2. The remaining leaves of the original Quire 'a' are foliated as ff. 3-8. In sequence and with reference to the foliation, the extant leaves are ff. i (left pastedown), 1-2 (inserted bifolium), 3-8.

handNote.p: Written in an early-13th century north European textualis formata.

decoNote.p: Historiated initial I on f. 12r with 7 scenes depiciting the seven days of creation as described in Genesis 1-2, each scene enclosed in a round frame in the body of the initial. Creation scenes are rendered on gold grounds, stamped with a floral or star motif. The upper and lower terminals of the initial are filled with foliate and zoomorphic interlace roundels in red, green, blue, pink, and white, but these sections have been damaged by over-trimming, presumably by later binders.

Coloured initials at the start of each biblical book. There are minor variations in the execution of these initials but all are typically 6-12 lines high, the body of the initial outlined in black and filled in gold, the counterspaces (i.e. the space inside an 'o') filled with a dark blue ground and white pen-flourished decoration, the initial enclosed entirely within a square or rectangular frame outlined in a dark pink and filled with a lighter pink decorated with small clusters of white dots. The remainder of the first word following the large initial is typically written as white Lombardic capitals on a dark blue rectangular ground.
Flourished initials at the openings of each Biblical chapter and other minor divisions of the text, either red initials with blue pen-flourishing or the reverse.
Running titles in the centre of the upper margin of each leaf (i.e., recto and verso) - written in Lombardic capitals, each letter written alternately in red or blue.
Plain coloured initials, red or blue, for each new item in the capitula lists.
Rubrication (red only) at the beginning of each preface and each biblical book.

msItem.note: The text referred to as '4 Esdras' in this manuscript (and generally so in western Europe in the Middle Ages) is now more commonly known as '2 Esdras'. The textual divisions of the medieval '4 Esdras' do not easily map onto the modern chapter and verse designations for 2 Esdras and so identification is made by comparing the textual content.

collation.p:
Quire of 8 with the 8th leaf missing.
Quire 468-1 (+2) (ff. 461-467, 469 + 470; 8th missing, ff. 469-470 are a tipped-in parchment bifolium)

The original structure of Quire 46 has been rearranged during later rebindings: a binder added a parchment bifolium after f. 467, then fixed the first leaf of the bifolium to the last extant leaf of Quire 46 with an adhesive and used the second leaf of the bifolium as the right pastedown. The original final leaf of Quire 46 (what would have been f. 468) is lost; due to historic foliation practice at Cambridge University Library, the lost leaf was included in the folio count when assigning folio designations, and so the foliation jumps from f. 467 to f. 469. The leaf-surfaces f. 467v and f. 469r are not visible as they are the interface by which the new bifolium was joined to the last extant leaf of Quire 46.
The CUL foliator, contrary to typical practice assigned a folio designation (f. 470) to the right pastedown.
